{#
===== FORM START =====

form_start(form, options): Generates opening <form> tag

What it generates:
<form method="POST" action="/current/url" onsubmit="return showSubmitInfo()">

Parameters:
1. form: The FormView object
2. {attr: {...}}: HTML attributes to add to <form> tag

attr: {onsubmit: "return showSubmitInfo()"}
- Adds custom JavaScript handler
- onsubmit fires when form is submitted
- "return showSubmitInfo()": Calls JavaScript function below
- If function returns false, form submission is cancelled
- If function returns true, form submission continues

Why use form_start() instead of plain <form>?
- Automatically sets correct action URL
- Automatically adds CSRF token for security
- Automatically sets method (POST by default)
- Can customize via options parameter
#}
{{ form_start(form, {
    attr: {
        onsubmit: "return showSubmitInfo()"
    }
}) }}

    {#
    ===== NAME FIELD =====

    form_row(form.name): Renders complete field with label, input, and errors

    What it generates:
    <div class="form-group">
        <label for="meal_name">Meal Name</label>
        <input type="text" id="meal_name" name="meal[name]" required>
        <span class="error">Error messages appear here if any</span>
    </div>

    form_row() is a convenience function that combines:
    - form_label(): Generates <label>
    - form_widget(): Generates <input> or other form element
    - form_errors(): Generates error messages

    Alternative manual approach:
    {{ form_label(form.name) }}
    {{ form_widget(form.name) }}
    {{ form_errors(form.name) }}

    But form_row() does all three at once!
    #}
    {{ form_row(form.name) }}

{#
===== ALLERGENS FIELD (CUSTOM LAYOUT) =====

Why custom layout instead of form_row()?
- We want checkboxes inside a <fieldset> with a <legend>
- This is better semantic HTML for grouped checkboxes
- Improves accessibility for screen readers

We manually combine the three parts:
1. form_label(): Label/legend
2. form_widget(): The actual checkboxes
3. form_errors(): Error messages
#}
<fieldset>
    {#
    form_label(form.allergens): Generates label text only

    Normally generates: <label>Allergens</label>
    But we put it inside <legend> for better semantics

    <fieldset> + <legend> is the proper HTML structure for:
    - Radio button groups
    - Checkbox groups
    - Related form fields
    #}
    <legend>{{ form_label(form.allergens) }}</legend>

    {#
    form_widget(form.allergens): Generates the actual form inputs

    For allergens field (configured in MealType as expanded: true),
    this generates multiple checkboxes:

    <input type="checkbox" name="meal[allergens][]" value="1"> A
    <input type="checkbox" name="meal[allergens][]" value="2"> C
    <input type="checkbox" name="meal[allergens][]" value="3"> D
    ...

    The [] in the name makes it an array in PHP
    PHP receives: ['allergens' => [1, 3, 5]]

    If expanded: false in MealType, would generate a <select multiple>
    #}
    {{ form_widget(form.allergens) }}

    {#
    form_errors(form.allergens): Displays validation errors

    If validation fails (e.g., data type mismatch), shows error message:
    <span class="error">This value is not valid.</span>

    If no errors, outputs nothing
    #}
    {{ form_errors(form.allergens) }}
</fieldset>

{{ form_row(form.nutritionalInfo) }}

<button class="btn btn-success">
    {{ button_label|default('Save') }}
</button>

{# ===== JAVASCRIPT FOR ALERT ===== #}
<script>
    function showSubmitInfo() {
        alert("{{ alert_text }}");
        return true;  // Allow form submission to continue
    }
</script>

{#
===== FORM END =====

form_end(form): Generates closing </form> tag and any remaining fields

What it does:
1. Renders any form fields not yet rendered
   (e.g., hidden fields, CSRF token)

2. Outputs closing </form> tag

#}
{{ form_end(form) }}
